solution:
A $135^\circ$ rotation around the origin in the clockwise direction corresponds to multiplication by $\operatorname{cis} 135^\circ = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} i.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A = (sqrt(2),-5*sqrt(2)), B = (4,6);

draw((-2,0)--(5,0));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8));
draw((0,0)--A,dashed);
draw((0,0)--B,dashed);

dot("$\sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i$", A, S);
dot("$4 + 6i$", B,  NE);
[/asy]

Thus, the image of $\sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i$ is
\[(\sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i) \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} i \right) = \boxed{4 + 6i}.\]

gptanswer:
We can represent $\sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i$ as the complex number $z = \sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i.$  Then $z$ has magnitude $\sqrt{(\sqrt{2})^2 + (-5 \sqrt{2})^2} = 7 \sqrt{2},$ and argument $\theta$ such that $\tan \theta = \frac{-5 \sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}} = -5.$  Since $\theta$ is in the third quadrant, $180^\circ < \theta < 270^\circ,$ so $\theta + 135^\circ$ is in the second quadrant.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair z = (sqrt(2),-5*sqrt(2));
pair w = rotate(135)*z;

draw((-8,0)--(8,0));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8));
draw((0,0)--z,Arrow(6));
draw((0,0)--w,Arrow(6));
draw(rightanglemark((0,0),(-1,-5),z,15));

label("$\sqrt{2}$", (sqrt(2)/2,0), S);
label("$5 \sqrt{2}$", (0,-5*sqrt(2)/2), W);
label("$z$", z, SE);
label("$w$", w, NW);
[/asy]

Then the complex number we seek is
\begin{align*}
w &= (\sqrt{2} - 5 \sqrt{2} i) \operatorname{cis} 135^\circ \\
&= 7 \sqrt{2} \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} i \right) \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} i \right) \\
&= \boxed{-6 + 6i}.
\end{align*}
